      "side": 1,
      "message": "Indeed, this can be confusing, and I had to look over https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/move_constructor to make sure I understood what\u0027s going on.\n\nFrom that site (slightly paraphrased) if the following conditions are met:\n- there are no user-declared copy constructors;\n- there are no user-declared copy assignment operators;\n- there are no user-declared move assignment operators;\n- there are no user-declared destructors;\n- the implicitly-declared move constructor is not defined as deleted\n\nthere is an implicitly declared move constructor.\n\nSkFrame has a user-declared destructor, so it doesn\u0027t get an implicitly declared move constructor. Without a move constructor for SkFrame, SkWebpCodec::Frame doesn\u0027t have an implicitly declared one, and cannot have a defaulted one, which would call through to the missing one in SkFrame. The existing code gets around this by explicitly defining SkWebpCodec::Frame\u0027s move constructor to call SkFrame\u0027s user-defined regular constructor.\n\nWith an explicit (default or otherwise) move constructor in SkFrame, SkWebpCodec::Frame now meets the conditions above, so an implicit move constructor is provided. This is why as your code is written SkWebpCodec::Frame can be used safely in a std::vector.",
